<SidebarLayout title="What is Spec-Driven Development? — gspec" description="An educational guide to Spec-Driven Development (SDD) — what it is, why it matters, common frameworks, and how it shapes modern software engineering.">
  <SidebarNav sections={sections} slot="sidebar" />
  <TableOfContents headings={headings} slot="toc" />

  <h1>What is Spec-Driven Development?</h1>
  <p class="text-lg text-[var(--text-secondary)] !mt-2 !mb-12">
    A comprehensive guide to building software from specifications — the philosophy, the frameworks, and why it matters more than ever.
  </p>

  <!-- Introduction -->
  <section id="introduction">
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Spec-Driven Development (SDD)</strong> is a software engineering methodology where formal specifications are written <em>before</em> implementation begins, and those specifications remain the authoritative source of truth throughout the project lifecycle. Rather than treating documentation as an afterthought, SDD makes specs the starting point — and the living backbone — of your software.
    </p>
    <p>
      The concept isn't new. Formal methods researchers in the 1970s and 1980s advocated for mathematical specifications before code. But the practice has evolved far beyond academic formalism. Today, SDD appears in many forms — from API contracts that generate server stubs, to behavior specifications that double as test suites, to product requirement documents that guide entire teams.
    </p>
    <p>
      What unites all flavors of SDD is a simple conviction: <strong>if you can't specify it clearly, you can't build it reliably.</strong>
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The Problem SDD Solves -->
  <section id="problem">
    <h2>The Problem SDD Solves</h2>
    <p>
      Most software projects don't fail because of bad code. They fail because of misalignment — between what the customer needs, what the product manager writes, what the designer envisions, and what the developer builds. Each handoff introduces drift.
    </p>
    <p>
      Consider the typical workflow without specifications:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>A product manager describes a feature in a meeting or a loose ticket</li>
      <li>A developer interprets it based on their understanding, makes dozens of micro-decisions</li>
      <li>A reviewer catches some issues but misses others</li>
      <li>The feature ships, and stakeholders say "that's not what I meant"</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      This isn't a people problem — it's a <strong>communication infrastructure problem</strong>. Natural language is ambiguous. Meetings are ephemeral. Tickets decay. Tribal knowledge doesn't scale.
    </p>
    <p>
      SDD addresses this by creating structured, unambiguous artifacts that everyone can reference. When a specification exists, disagreements surface <em>before</em> code is written — when they're cheap to resolve — rather than after, when they're expensive.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Core Principles -->
  <section id="core-principles">
    <h2>Core Principles</h2>
    <p>
      While SDD frameworks differ in scope and syntax, they share a set of core principles:
    </p>

    <h3>1. Specs Come First</h3>
    <p>
      Implementation follows specification, not the other way around. This doesn't mean you need a complete spec before writing any code — iterative refinement is fine — but the spec should lead, not trail.
    </p>

    <h3>2. Specs Are Authoritative</h3>
    <p>
      When the spec and the code disagree, one of them needs to change. In SDD, the spec is the source of truth. If the implementation diverges, either the code is wrong or the spec needs to be updated intentionally — never silently.
    </p>

    <h3>3. Specs Are Structured</h3>
    <p>
      A spec is not a wiki page or a Confluence document with screenshots. SDD specs use consistent formats — schemas, structured markdown, formal grammars, or domain-specific languages — so they can be parsed, validated, and acted upon.
    </p>

    <h3>4. Specs Are Living Documents</h3>
    <p>
      Specifications are not write-once artifacts. They evolve alongside the software. The key distinction from traditional documentation is that specs are updated <em>as part of</em> the development process, not after it.
    </p>

    <h3>5. Specs Enable Automation</h3>
    <p>
      Well-structured specs can drive code generation, test creation, validation, documentation rendering, and more. The more machine-readable your specs, the more leverage you get from them.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The SDD Workflow -->
  <section id="sdd-workflow">
    <h2>The SDD Workflow</h2>
    <p>
      While specific implementations vary, the general SDD workflow follows a consistent pattern:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Define</strong> — Write the specification. This might be an API schema, a behavioral scenario, a product requirements document, or an architecture decision record.</li>
      <li><strong>Validate</strong> — Review the spec with stakeholders. Catch misunderstandings, missing edge cases, and contradictions before any code is written.</li>
      <li><strong>Implement</strong> — Build the software to satisfy the specification. The spec serves as both a guide and a contract.</li>
      <li><strong>Verify</strong> — Confirm that the implementation matches the spec. This can be automated (contract tests, schema validation) or manual (acceptance review).</li>
      <li><strong>Evolve</strong> — When requirements change, update the spec first, then update the code. The spec always reflects the intended state of the system.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      This loop — define, validate, implement, verify, evolve — is the heartbeat of SDD. The specific tools and formats change, but the cycle remains constant.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- SDD Frameworks & Approaches -->
  <section id="frameworks">
    <h2>Common SDD Frameworks & Approaches</h2>
    <p>
      Spec-Driven Development is not a single tool or methodology — it's a family of practices. Here are the most widely adopted approaches, each targeting different layers of the software stack.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- OpenAPI / Swagger -->
  <section id="openapi">
    <h3>OpenAPI / Swagger</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>OpenAPI</strong> (formerly Swagger) is perhaps the most successful SDD framework in production use today. It provides a standard, machine-readable format for describing RESTful APIs.
    </p>
    <p>
      An OpenAPI specification defines endpoints, request/response schemas, authentication methods, and error codes in YAML or JSON. From this single spec, teams can generate:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Server stubs in dozens of languages</li>
      <li>Client SDKs for consumers</li>
      <li>Interactive API documentation (Swagger UI, Redoc)</li>
      <li>Contract tests that verify implementation matches the spec</li>
      <li>Mock servers for frontend development</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The "API-first" movement, championed by companies like Stripe and Twilio, is built on this approach. Teams design the API contract before writing implementation code, enabling frontend and backend teams to work in parallel against the shared spec.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Scope:</strong> API interfaces. OpenAPI excels at defining the contract between services but doesn't address product requirements, visual design, or architecture decisions.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Behavior-Driven Development -->
  <section id="bdd">
    <h3>Behavior-Driven Development (BDD)</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>BDD</strong>, pioneered by Dan North and popularized by tools like <strong>Cucumber</strong>, <strong>SpecFlow</strong>, and <strong>Behave</strong>, uses natural-language scenarios as specifications. These scenarios are written in <strong>Gherkin</strong> syntax:
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong>Given</strong> a user is logged in<br />
        <strong>When</strong> they click "Create Task"<br />
        <strong>Then</strong> a new task form should appear
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      The power of BDD is that specs are simultaneously human-readable and machine-executable. Product managers can read and write scenarios, and developers wire them to step definitions that drive automated tests.
    </p>
    <p>
      BDD bridges the gap between business requirements and test automation. The spec <em>is</em> the test. When a scenario fails, you know exactly which business behavior broke.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Scope:</strong> Feature behavior and acceptance criteria. BDD is excellent for defining what the system should do from a user's perspective but doesn't prescribe architecture, technology choices, or visual design.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Design by Contract -->
  <section id="dbc">
    <h3>Design by Contract (DbC)</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Design by Contract</strong>, formalized by Bertrand Meyer in the Eiffel programming language, embeds specifications directly into code. Every method declares:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Preconditions</strong> — what must be true before the method runs</li>
      <li><strong>Postconditions</strong> — what the method guarantees upon completion</li>
      <li><strong>Invariants</strong> — what must always be true about the object's state</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      These contracts are checked at runtime (and sometimes at compile time), turning specifications into enforceable agreements between components. Languages like Eiffel have native support; others use libraries (e.g., <code>contracts</code> in Python, <code>cofoja</code> for Java).
    </p>
    <p>
      DbC influenced modern type systems, assertion libraries, and tools like Microsoft's Code Contracts. TypeScript's type system, Zod validation schemas, and Rust's ownership model all carry echoes of contract-based thinking.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Scope:</strong> Code-level interfaces and invariants. DbC operates at the function and class level — it doesn't address system architecture, product requirements, or cross-service contracts.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Model-Driven Development -->
  <section id="mdd">
    <h3>Model-Driven Development (MDD)</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Model-Driven Development</strong> takes SDD to a higher abstraction level. Instead of writing specs in text, teams build formal models (often visual) that describe the system's structure and behavior. Tools then generate code from these models.
    </p>
    <p>
      Common MDD approaches include:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>UML</strong> — Unified Modeling Language for system design (class diagrams, sequence diagrams, state machines)</li>
      <li><strong>Domain-Specific Languages (DSLs)</strong> — Custom languages for specific problem domains (e.g., SQL for data, Terraform for infrastructure)</li>
      <li><strong>Schema-first ORMs</strong> — Tools like Prisma and Drizzle where you define your data model in a schema file and generate database migrations and type-safe clients</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The promise of MDD is that the model captures intent at a level above code, reducing translation errors. In practice, the approach works best for well-understood domains with stable patterns — database schemas, state machines, infrastructure configuration.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Scope:</strong> System structure and behavior models. MDD is powerful for architecture and data modeling but is rarely used for product requirements or visual design.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Architecture Decision Records -->
  <section id="adrs">
    <h3>Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>ADRs</strong>, popularized by Michael Nygard, are lightweight documents that capture significant architectural decisions. Each ADR records:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Context</strong> — what situation or problem prompted the decision</li>
      <li><strong>Decision</strong> — what was decided and why</li>
      <li><strong>Status</strong> — proposed, accepted, deprecated, or superseded</li>
      <li><strong>Consequences</strong> — what trade-offs and implications follow</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      ADRs solve a specific problem in SDD: <em>why</em> was a technical choice made? Six months later, when someone asks "why did we choose PostgreSQL over MongoDB?", the ADR has the answer — with the original context intact.
    </p>
    <p>
      Tools like <code>adr-tools</code>, Log4brains, and simple markdown files in an <code>docs/adr/</code> directory make ADRs easy to adopt. They're version-controlled alongside the code, evolving as decisions are revisited.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Scope:</strong> Architectural decisions and their rationale. ADRs capture the "why" behind technical choices but don't define APIs, features, or visual design.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- PRDs & Product Specs -->
  <section id="prds">
    <h3>PRDs & Product Specifications</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>Product Requirements Documents (PRDs)</strong> are the oldest form of specification in software. They define what a product should do from the user's perspective — features, user stories, acceptance criteria, and scope boundaries.
    </p>
    <p>
      Modern PRDs have evolved significantly from the 50-page Word documents of the waterfall era. Today's product specs tend to be:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Lean</strong> — focused on outcomes, not implementation details</li>
      <li><strong>Structured</strong> — using consistent templates with prioritized capabilities</li>
      <li><strong>Iterative</strong> — refined as understanding grows</li>
      <li><strong>Testable</strong> — each requirement has clear acceptance criteria</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Tools and frameworks in this space include JIRA epics/stories, Linear project specs, Notion templates, Shape Up pitches, Amazon's Working Backwards press releases, and various internal PRD templates at tech companies.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Scope:</strong> Product requirements and user-facing behavior. PRDs define what to build and why, but they don't specify technical implementation, API contracts, or code-level design.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Benefits of SDD -->
  <section id="benefits">
    <h2>Benefits of SDD</h2>
    <p>
      Organizations that adopt spec-driven practices consistently report several advantages:
    </p>

    <h3>Reduced Ambiguity</h3>
    <p>
      Structured specifications force clarity. Vague requirements like "the system should be fast" become concrete: "API responses must complete within 200ms at the 95th percentile." Disagreements are surfaced during spec review, not during code review or QA.
    </p>

    <h3>Parallel Development</h3>
    <p>
      When a contract is defined upfront, teams can work in parallel. Frontend and backend teams build against the same API spec. Multiple developers implement different features against the same architecture document. The spec acts as a coordination mechanism without requiring constant synchronization.
    </p>

    <h3>Better Onboarding</h3>
    <p>
      New team members can read the specs to understand the system — its purpose, its architecture, its design decisions, and its feature requirements. This is dramatically faster than piecing together understanding from code, comments, and oral history.
    </p>

    <h3>Automated Validation</h3>
    <p>
      Machine-readable specs enable automated tooling: contract tests, schema validation, documentation generation, code generation, and consistency checks. The spec becomes infrastructure, not just documentation.
    </p>

    <h3>Reduced Rework</h3>
    <p>
      Finding a requirement error during spec review costs minutes. Finding it after implementation costs hours or days. Finding it after deployment costs significantly more. SDD shifts discovery left, where the cost of change is lowest.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Challenges & Trade-offs -->
  <section id="challenges">
    <h2>Challenges & Trade-offs</h2>
    <p>
      SDD is not without costs. Understanding the trade-offs helps teams adopt it effectively.
    </p>

    <h3>Upfront Investment</h3>
    <p>
      Writing specifications takes time. For rapid prototyping or exploratory work, the overhead may not be justified. SDD delivers the most value when the cost of misalignment is high — larger teams, longer-lived projects, complex domains.
    </p>

    <h3>Spec Drift</h3>
    <p>
      The biggest risk in SDD is specs that fall out of sync with reality. When the code evolves but the spec doesn't, the spec becomes misleading — worse than having no spec at all. Successful SDD requires discipline and tooling to keep specs current.
    </p>

    <h3>Over-Specification</h3>
    <p>
      There's a tension between thoroughness and agility. Specs that are too detailed become rigid and resist change. Specs that are too vague provide insufficient guidance. Finding the right level of detail is a skill that improves with practice.
    </p>

    <h3>Tooling Fragmentation</h3>
    <p>
      Most SDD frameworks address only one layer of the stack. A team might use OpenAPI for APIs, Gherkin for behavior, ADRs for architecture, and PRDs for features — each with its own format, tooling, and workflow. This fragmentation can create its own coordination overhead.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- SDD in the AI Era -->
  <section id="ai-era">
    <h2>SDD in the AI Era</h2>
    <p>
      The rise of AI-assisted coding tools has given Spec-Driven Development new urgency and new capabilities.
    </p>
    <p>
      AI coding assistants are remarkably capable at generating code, but they face a fundamental challenge: <strong>they don't know what you're building</strong>. Without context about your product's purpose, your design language, your technology choices, and your engineering standards, AI tools make reasonable-sounding but often wrong assumptions.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is where SDD and AI become natural partners. Specifications give AI tools the structured context they need to generate code that actually fits your project:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Product specs</strong> tell the AI <em>who</em> you're building for and <em>why</em></li>
      <li><strong>Design specs</strong> ensure generated UI matches your visual language</li>
      <li><strong>Technology specs</strong> prevent the AI from choosing the wrong framework or library</li>
      <li><strong>Architecture specs</strong> guide the AI toward your established patterns</li>
      <li><strong>Feature specs</strong> give the AI scoped, testable requirements to build against</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Without specs, every AI interaction starts from zero — you re-explain your stack, your patterns, your preferences. With specs, the AI has persistent, structured context that compounds across interactions.
    </p>
    <p>
      This shift is turning SDD from a "nice to have" discipline into a practical multiplier for AI-assisted development. Teams with good specs get dramatically better output from AI tools than teams without.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Where gspec Fits -->
  <section id="gspec">
    <h2>Where gspec Fits</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>gspec</strong> is one implementation of Spec-Driven Development, designed specifically for the AI-assisted development workflow. Understanding how it relates to the frameworks above helps clarify its role.
    </p>

    <h3>What gspec Does Differently</h3>
    <p>
      Most SDD frameworks target a single layer — OpenAPI for APIs, BDD for behavior, ADRs for decisions. gspec takes a <strong>full-stack specification approach</strong>, covering the entire surface area of a product across multiple spec types:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Product identity</strong> (profile) — like a lean PRD for your product's purpose</li>
      <li><strong>Visual design</strong> (style) — design tokens and component patterns</li>
      <li><strong>Technology choices</strong> (stack) — frameworks, infrastructure, and rationale</li>
      <li><strong>Engineering standards</strong> (practices) — coding conventions and workflows</li>
      <li><strong>System architecture</strong> (architecture) — data models, APIs, project structure</li>
      <li><strong>Feature requirements</strong> (features) — prioritized capabilities with acceptance criteria</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>How gspec Compares</h3>
    <p>
      Here's how gspec relates to the established SDD approaches:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>vs. OpenAPI</strong> — OpenAPI goes deeper on API contract details (request/response schemas, status codes, authentication). gspec's architecture spec covers API design at a higher level. They're complementary — you might use gspec for the overall system design and OpenAPI for detailed API contracts.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>vs. BDD/Cucumber</strong> — BDD scenarios are executable tests. gspec feature specs define requirements and acceptance criteria but don't execute directly. BDD is better for automated acceptance testing; gspec is better for guiding AI implementation.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>vs. ADRs</strong> — ADRs capture individual decisions with rationale. gspec's stack and architecture specs capture the current state of decisions in a consolidated form. ADRs provide better historical context; gspec provides a better current snapshot for AI tools.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>vs. MDD/UML</strong> — Model-driven approaches use formal visual models and code generation. gspec uses structured Markdown — more accessible, easier to version, and optimized for LLM consumption rather than diagram tooling.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>vs. Traditional PRDs</strong> — gspec feature specs are structured like modern PRDs but designed to be machine-readable and to live alongside the code in version control, not in a separate tool like Notion or Confluence.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>When to Use What</h3>
    <p>
      SDD frameworks are not mutually exclusive. A well-run project might use several:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>gspec</strong> for full-stack product specifications that guide AI-assisted development</li>
      <li><strong>OpenAPI</strong> for detailed, machine-enforceable API contracts between services</li>
      <li><strong>BDD</strong> for executable acceptance tests tied to business scenarios</li>
      <li><strong>ADRs</strong> for preserving the historical context behind architectural decisions</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The right choice depends on your team, your tools, and what problems you're solving. The important thing is that you're writing specifications at all — the specific framework matters less than the discipline of thinking before coding.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you're interested in trying gspec, check out the <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}getting-started/`}>Getting Started guide</a> or explore the <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}docs/`}>full documentation</a>.
    </p>
  </section>
</SidebarLayout>
